      "text": "Two valuable insights emerge from part 1 in this regard. First of all, for those inclined to view the industrial firm as an organization separate and distinct from all other large systems, requiring conscious control at all levels, Beer demonstrates that certain principles of innate control or [[self-organization]] apply to all large systems, including the industrial firm. The key to effective management, therefore, is to understand the nature of self-organization and the principles that govern the same, in order to be able \"to facilitate regulation without imposing it\" (p. 16)."
